<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-10-17T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-10-17T16:00:00-05:00" n="921" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d921">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">711.4112A/29: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Houghton</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-10-17T16:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">October 17,
                                        1928—4 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>231. Instruction No. 1437 of May 22, 1928. Embassy’s No. 88, April 27,
                            1928, 2 p.m.<note n="11" xml:id="d921fn11"><ref target="frus1928v01#pg_39">Vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p.
                                    39</ref>.</note> Arbitration Treaty.</p>
                        <p>The suggestion of the British Ambassador that the Arbitration Treaty of
                            1908, which expired June 4, should be prolonged proved <pb facs="1066" n="948" xml:id="pg_948"/> impracticable and nothing has since been
                            received from the British Government in regard to negotiation of new
                            treaty.</p>
                        <p>Please inquire at the Foreign Office whether it will shortly furnish the
                            British Embassy in Washington with instructions. An early reply is
                            desired.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Clark</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
